observations.recommendation:
We have recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor creates a GFPS Execom, TWG and Secretariat that will supervise, advocate and install a GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) as well as the required Gender Responsive Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) System;
 The Municipal Mayor with the help of the Sangguniang Bayan, formulate and adapt a Local GAD Code;
The MSWDO being the leading authority in identifying gender related issues and concerns, see to it that GAD activities are identified through the use of HGDG and that the GAD plan are regularly updated; and
Henceforth, management sees to it that said plan and budget are approved by the DILG and the PPDO.

23.2.5	We have recommended the management to comply with the requirement of Section 37(C), Rule VI of RA No. 7160 or the Magna Carta of Women and Section 4.1.A of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, on the creation of the GAD Focal Point System.
23.3.5	We have recommended management to see to it that GAD activities are identified through the use of HGDG, that the GAD plan are regularly updated and that the identified projects do address the GAD issues and concern in the long run;
23.5.3	For observation letter 23.4 and 23.5, we have recommended management to follow the prescribed format of GAD plan and see to it that said plan and budget are approved by the DILG and the PPDO;
23.6.6	We have recommended management to initiate the strengthening of the Gender and Development Inter-Agency Committee by solidification of its Gender Responsive Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) System to execute proper determination of GAD objectives and accomplishment of projects.
23.7.4	We have recommended management to maximize the utilization of the GAD funds through the implementation of GAD related PPAs in order to achieve the objective for which funds were provided.

We have recommended the following:

The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer exert effort in determining the composition of unliquidated cash advances in the previous years;
Send demand letters to the officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances;
Management demand from the retired MPDC the refund of payment of loan amortization amounting to ₱199,632.08. Consider withholding any retirement benefits due him which can be legally withheld.  Otherwise, this will become the personal liability of the person responsible for the remittance thereof; and
Management refrain from granting cash advance to elective officials for purposes other than travelling expenses.

7.5	In view of the above noted lapses, we have recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer exert effort in determining the composition of unliquidated cash advances in the previous years;
Send demand letters to the officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances;
Management demand from the retired MPDC the refund of payment of loan amortization amounting to ₱199,632.08. Consider withholding any retirement benefits due him which can be legally withheld.  Otherwise, this will become the personal liability of the person responsible for the remittance thereof; and
Management refrain from granting cash advance to elective officials for purposes other than travelling expenses.

We have recommended that the management:

Justify the noted lapses;
Allocate at least 30% of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund for the Quick Response Fund to be utilized during disasters and calamities;
Require the MDRRMO-Designate to prepare and submit to the audit team the report of utilization of the LDRRMF. Henceforth, utilization reports should be submitted on the prescribed time set forth by the COA Circular No. 2012-002.
Require the Sangguniang Bayan to pass a resolution for the opening of a special trust fund account for the unexpended balance of the fund
